{"title_page": "Ulcinj", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox settlement-->\n| native_name                     = \u0423\u043b\u0446\u0438\u045a<br>Ulqin\n| name                            = Ulcinj\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of cities in Montenegro|Town]] and [[Municipalities of Montenegro|municipality]]\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{MNE}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Municipalities of Montenegro|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Ulcinj Municipality]]\n| timezone                        = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset                      = +1\n| image_skyline                   = Ulcinj, Montenegro - Sept. 2010.jpg\n| map_caption                     = Location of Ulcinj, Montenegro.\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = +2\n| population_as_of                = 2011 census\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Loro Nrekiq\n| leader_party                    = [[Democratic Party of Socialists of Montenegro|DPS]]\n| leader_title1                   = Ruling&nbsp;party\n| area_total_km2                  = 255\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_blank1               = 19,921\n| population_blank1_title         = Municipality\n| population_density_km2          = 79.47\n| population_urban                = 10,707\n| population_rural                = 9,214\n| population_demonym              = Ulcinjani<br />Ulqinak\u00eb\n| parts                           = 39\n| parts_type                      = Settlements\n| established_date                = 5th century BC\n| pushpin_map                     = Montenegro\n| pushpin_label_position          = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location of Ulcinj\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|41.92|19.20|region:ME|display=inline,title}}\n| area_code_type                  = [[Telephone numbers in Montenegro|Area code]]\n| area_code                       = +382&nbsp;30\n| blank1_info_sec1                = UL\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Vehicle registration plates of Montenegro|Car&nbsp;plates]]\n| postal_code_type                = [[List of postal codes in Montenegro|Postal code]]\n| postal_code                     = 85360\n| blank_info_sec1                 = ME-20\n| blank_name_sec1                 = [[ISO 3166-2:ME|ISO 3166-2&nbsp;code]]\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.ul-gov.me|Official Website}}\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_shield                    = Coat of Arms of Ulcinj.svg\n| shield_alt                      = [[Coat of arms of Ulcinj|Coat of arms]]\n}}\n\n'''Ulcinj''' ([[Montenegrin Cyrillic]]: \u0423\u043b\u0446\u0438\u045a, {{IPA-sh|\u01d4lt\u0361si\u0272|pron}}) or ([[Albanian language|Albanian]] : '''Ulqin''' or ''Ulqini'') is a town on the southern coast of [[Montenegro]] and the capital of [[Ulcinj Municipality]]. It has an urban population of 10,707 (2011), the majority being [[Albanians]].\n\nAs one of the oldest settlements in the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic coast]], it was founded in 5th century BC. It was captured by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] in 163 BC from the [[Illyrians]]. With the division of the [[Roman Empire]], it became part of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. It was known as a base for [[piracy]].\n\nDuring the [[Middle Ages]] it was under [[South Slavs|South Slavic]] rule for a few centuries. In 1405 it became part of [[Republic of Venice]] and in 1571 part of [[Ottoman Empire]]. Ulcinj was ceded to the [[Principality of Montenegro]] in 1878. It is a former medieval Catholic bishopric and remains a Latin [[titular see]].\n\nUlcinj is a destination for tourists, because of its [[Velika Pla\u017ea|Long Beach]], [[Lake \u0160as]], [[Ada Bojana|Ada Bojana Island]] and for its two-millennia-old [[Ulcinj Castle]]. Ulcinj is also the centre of the [[Albanians in Montenegro|Albanian community in Montenegro]].\n\n== Names ==\nEarly historian [[Livy]] (59 BC\u2013AD 17) mentioned it,<ref name=\"Mijovi\u01071970\">{{cite book|author=Pavle Mijovi\u0107|title=Tragom drevnih kultura Crne Gore|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ef0bAAAAMAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Grafi\u010dki zavod|page=35}}</ref> as did [[Pliny the Elder]] (23\u201379),<ref name=\"PraschnikerSchober1976\">{{cite book|author1=C. Praschniker|author2=A. Schober|title=Arch?ologische Forschungen in Albanien und Montenegro|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DO4JAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA82|year=1976|publisher=\u0420\u0438\u043f\u043e\u043b \u041a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043a|isbn=978-5-87379-103-3|pages=82\u2013}}</ref> who mentioned it as ''Olcinium'', its old name ''Colchinium'', \"founded by [settlers from] [[Colchis]]\" (Olchinium quod antea Colchinium dictum est a Colchis conditum).<ref name=\"PraschnikerSchober1976\"/> [[Ptolemy]] (90\u2013168) mentions the city as Greek ''Oulkinion'' (\u039f\u03c5\u03bb\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd).<ref>{{cite book|title=Claudii Ptolemaei Geographia edidit Carolus Fridericus Augustus Nobbe|volume=1|chapter=16|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BKJA_GDRGT4C|year=1843|publisher=sumptibus et typis Caroli Tauchnitii|page=134}}</ref> Although the ancient writers preferred a connection with Cholchis, the name of the settlement appears to be connected with the [[Albanian language|Albanian]] word ''ujk'' or ''ulk'' (meaning [[wolf]] in [[English language|English]]),<ref name=\"Wilkes244\">{{cite book|last=Wilkes|first=John|title=The Illyrians|year=1992|publisher=Wiley|isbn=9780631146711|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=l8q0QgAACAAJ&dq=Wilkes%20the%20illyrians&source=gbs_book_other_versions|pages=244|ref=harv}} \"Names of individuals peoples may have been formed in a similar fashion, Taulantii from \u2018swallow\u2019 (cf. the Albanian tallandushe) or Erchelei the \u2018eel-men\u2019 and Chelidoni the \u2018snail-men\u2019. The name of the Delmatae appears connected with the Albanian word for \u2018sheep\u2019 delm\u00eb) and the Dardanians with for \u2018pear\u2019 (dardh\u00eb). Some place names appear to have similar derivations, including Olcinium (Ulcinj from \u2018wolf\u2019 (ukas), although the ancients preferred a connection with Cholchis.\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|last= Birnbaum|first=Henrik|last2=Puhvel|first2=Jaan|title=Ancient Indo-European Dialects|chapter=The Position of Albanian|year=1963|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=|url=https://books.google.it/books?id=5pCBRsfJMv8C&vq|page=108|ref=harv}}</ref> from [[Proto-Albanian language|Proto-Albanian]] ''*(w)ulka'', from [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] ''*w\u013a\u0325k\u02b7os''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Orel|first=Vladimir|title=Albanian etymological dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yJQYAQAAIAAJ&dq|year=1998|publisher=Brill|isbn=9004110240|p=484}}</ref> The name, through Late (Vulgar) Roman, became [[Middle Latin]] '''Ulcinium''', {{lang-it|Dulcigno}} ({{IPA-it|dul\u02c8t\u0283i\u0272\u0272o|pron}}), [[Slavic languages|Slavic]]: ''Ulcinj'', {{lang-sq|Ulqin}} or ''Ulqini'' and {{lang-tr|\u00dclg\u00fcn}}.\n\n== Geography ==\n\n=== Neighbourhoods ===\n*''\u00c7arshia'' (mn. ''\u010car\u0161ija''), is a [[neighborhood]] and town centre which connects the old and new parts (neighbourhoods). In 2009 it was reconstructed, with the [[asphalt concrete|asphalt]] being changed into [[sett (paving)|sett]] and the water and electrical system were changed. The neighbourhood has some 200 shops. It has an oriental atmosphere. There are two [[mosques]] located in this area, the [[Namazgjahu Mosque]] and [[Kryepazari Mosque]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Antiquity ===\nUlcinj is an ancient seaport.<ref name= Rellie>{{cite book |title= Montenegro|last= Rellie |first= Annalisa |year=2012 |publisher= The Globe Pequot Press Inc |location= Bradt Travel Guides Ltd, IDC House, The Vale, Chalfront St Peter, Bucks SL9 9RZ, England|isbn=978 1 84162 381 8  |pages=207\u2013208 |url= https://books.google.com.au/books?id=L0Apj11ifqUC&pg=PA206&dq=Ulcinj&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GrbBUZ2lLqWkigK9l4DADA&ved=0CFcQ6AEwBw|accessdate=2013-06-20}}</ref> The wider area of Ulcinj has been inhabited since the [[Bronze Age]], based on dating of [[Illyrians|Illyrian]] tombs (tumuli) found in the village of [[Zogaj, Shkod\u00ebr|Zogaj]], in the vicinity of Ulcinj. The town is believed to have been founded in the 5th century BC by colonists from [[Colchis]], as mentioned in the 3rd century BC poem by [[Apollonius of Rhodes]]. Illyrians lived in the region at the time as there are traces of immense [[Cyclopean walls]] still visible in the old Citadel.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nAll the way in the pre-medieval period, Ulcinj was known as one of the pirate capitals of the [[Adriatic Sea]]. This is also seen during the later period of [[Illyrian Kingdom]]. Inhabitants of Ulcinj were known before time of [[Christ]], especially from 20 BC to around 300 AD, to be very confrontational to those who were foreigners to their land; they were especially meticulous about border disputes as well.\n\n=== Roman ===\n[[File:Roman_Doclea.gif|thumb|Roman Doclea]]\nIn 168 BC, during the [[Third Illyrian War]], Olcinium broke with [[Gentius]] and defected to the Romans ([[Livy]] 45:26:2). Under Roman rule the town received the status of ''oppidum civium Romanorum'' (settlement of Roman citizens), only to be later granted ''[[municipium]]'' (independent town) status. A section of their re-fortification can be distinguished from the Illyrio-Greek by the rustication of the walls.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nThe ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea|Periplus Maris Erythraei]]'' names several Indian ports [[Indian_maritime_history#Early_Common_Era\u2014High_Middle_Ages|from where large ships sailed]] in an easterly direction to ''[[Ulcinj|Khruse]]'' (Kru\u010de - seaside village in Ulcinj).<ref>Donkin, Robin A. (2003), ''Between East and West: The Moluccas and the Traffic in Spices Up to the Arrival of Europeans'', Diane Publishing Company, {{ISBN|0-87169-248-1}}, page. 64</ref> \n\nAfter the division of the Roman Empire, Ulcinj became a part of the Byzantine province of [[Prevalis]] and the population converted to Christianity. From Medieval times, and quiet likely earlier, it was regarded as an important trading and maritime center and still maintained the status of city autonomy.<ref name= Rellie/> From circa 820, the city was the see of a [[Diocese of Ulcinj]], which was only suppressed in 1532, and would be revived as a Latin [[titular bishopric]].\n\n=== Medieval period and South Slavic rule ===\nIn the 9th century, it was in the [[Dyrrhachium (theme)|Dyrrhachium theme]], a military governorate of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. In 1010, ''Tsar'' [[Samuel of Bulgaria]] (r. 997-1014\u2020) failed to conquer the town during the [[Byzantine-Bulgarian Wars#Sviatoslav.27s invasion and the Byzantine conquest of Bulgaria|war against the Byzantines]].\n \nBy 1040, ''archon'' [[Vojislav of Duklja|Stefan Vojislav]] of [[Duklja]] conquered the region. In 1183, [[Serbian Grand Principality|Serbian Prince]] [[Stefan Nemanja]] conquered Olcinium and the town prospered as one of the most significant coastal towns. Ulcinj remained in Nemanji\u0107 hands in their [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Kingdom]] and [[Serbian Empire|Empire]], and after the death of [[Emperor Du\u0161an]] (r. 1331-1355\u2020), the region, known as ''Lower [[Lordship of Zeta|Zeta]]'', was under the supervision of ''gospodin'' [[\u017darko (nobleman)|\u017darko]], a ''voivode'' of Emperor [[Uro\u0161 the Weak]] until his death in 1360. \u017darko's lands were then held by the [[Bal\u0161i\u0107]] family. Under Bal\u0161i\u0107 control, Ulcinj continued to be an important town and also [[Mint (coin)|minted coins]]. The Bal\u0161i\u0107 Tower in the upper part of the Old Town was built by the [[Bal\u0161i\u0107 noble family]] in the late 14th century.\n\n=== Venetian and Ottoman rule ===\n[[File:Dulcingo Pinargenti 1573.jpg|thumb|Map of Dulcigno (now Ulcinj) in 1573 by Simon Pinargenti]]\nIn 1405 the Venetians conquered the town. Under Venetian control, the city was renamed ''Dulcigno'' in [[Italian language|Italian]], and it was incorporated in the [[Albania Veneta]]. The Venetians maintained control until 1571, when the [[Ottoman Turks]] conquered Dulcigno with the help of [[Barbary pirates]], who didn't leave the town after conquering. It remained within the Ottoman domain for over 300 years, during which time its far-reaching reputation as a lair of pirates was established.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nIn the 17th century a self-proclaimed Jewish [[Messiah]] named [[Sabbatai Zevi]] caused turmoil throughout the Turkish Empire with his evangelizing, which attracted thousands of followers. He was eventually captured and exiled to Ulcinj in 1666, where he died quietly ten years later. He was buried in the courtyard of a Muslim house which is still preserved as a mausoleum; along with two Jewish altars in the Bal\u0161ic Tower.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nIn 1867, Ulcinj became a [[township|kaza]] of the [[Sanjak of Scutari|\u0130\u015fkodra sanjak]] of [[Rumeli]] veyalet. After the [[Congress of Berlin]] in 1878, borders between Montenegro and the Ottoman Empire were redrawn, with [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]] and [[Gusinje]] being ceded to Montenegro. But Muslim Albanian resistance prevented the Montenegrins from taking over Plav and Gusinje, so the Great Powers in 1880 decided to reverse the territorial transfer and offered Ulcinj to Montenegro as compensation.\n\n=== 20th century to present ===\n[[File:Fish-market in Ulcinj (1908).jpg|thumb|Ulcinj fish market in 1908]]\nUlcinj became a part of the [[Kingdom of Montenegro]] from 1878 until 1918 when Montenegro was absorbed into the [[Kingdom of Serbia]] for a short time before all would be incorporated into the first of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] federations at the end of the year. Ulcinj remained within a Montenegrin entity whilst a South Slavic state had existed until 2006 when which it became part of an independent Montenegro following a referendum.\n\nDuring the 20th century, Ulcinj survived heavy declines and new ascents. Ulcinj was the second biggest town of Montenegro when it joined the kingdom in 1880. In just three decades, it backslided to 6th place for economic development and number of inhabitants (after Podgorica, Niksic, Cetinje, Tivar and Plava). During World War I Ulcinj was conquered by Austria-Hungary in 1916 and Italy on November 4, 1918,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://augusto.digitpa.gov.it/gazzette/index/download/id/1918261_PM|title=Gazzetta Ufficiale del Regno d'Italia N. 261 del 6 Novembre 1918|last=|first=|date=6 November 1918|work=Gazzetta Ufficiale del Regno d'Italia|accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> and since 1920 it was part of the Serbo-Croatian-Slovenian Kingdom, later known as the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]].\n\nAs the southernmost city of the coast of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia, Ulcinj had a strong turnaround in the 1930s with the development of the tourist industry. At that time hotels were built such as Kri\u0161tja, Republic, Jadran and Koop (later Galeb). \nWorld War II halted economic momentum. From 1941 to 1944, Ulcinj was under the Albanian administration. On November 7, 1943, Ulcinj was bombarded by Allied forces, with over 46 people  killed and many more injured. The [[Yugoslav Partisans]] took Ulcinj on November 26, 1944, and the city become part of [[Socialist Yugoslavia]]. <ref>[[#LTKU-1989|LTKU (1989)]], fq. 46</ref><ref>[http://www.cdm.me/politika/cetkovic-dps-i-forca-hoce-da-brisu-istoriju-ulcinja \u0106etkovi\u0107: DPS i Forca ho\u0107e da bri\u0161u istoriju Ulcinja]</ref><ref>[http://www.visit-ulcinj.com/blog/2014/03/19/ruzna-strana-lepote-ulcinja/ Ru\u017ena strana lepote Ulcinja]</ref>\n\nThe 1950s and 1960s marked the gratest period of economic development for Ulcinj, with the construction of a range of modern hotels in the city and the Great Plain, as well as major economic collectives (NHT \"Riviera of Ulcinj\", \"Agroulqini\", Primary Building Company, \"Otrantkomerc\", \"Ultep\" and others). In the catastrophic earthquake on April 15, 1979, the city was severely damaged, but after only a few years, with the solidarity of the citizens of entire Yugoslavia, it was quickly renovated. Ulcinj at the end of the eighties had about 40 percent of the tourist turnover in Montenegro, while two-thirds of the guests were foreign, mostly German.\n\nDuring the Kosovo War, in 1998 and 1999, thousands of Kosovo Albanians flocked to Ulcinj and its surroundings, where they were welcomed in the best possible conditions by the ethnic Albanian population of Ulcinj and the surrounding area.\n\n== Population ==\n{{Historical populations\n| 1948|4385\n| 1953|4919\n| 1961|5705\n| 1971|7459\n| 1981|9140\n| 1991|10025\n| 2003|10828\n| 2011|10707\n|footnote=\n}}\nUlcinj is the administrative centre of [[Ulcinj Municipality]], which has a population of 19,921. The town of Ulcinj itself has a population of 10,707. Ulcinj Municipality is the centre of the [[Albanians in Montenegro|Albanian community in Montenegro]]. It is one of two municipalities in Montenegro where [[Albanians]] form the majority with 70%, the other being [[Tuzi Municipality|Tuzi]] with a 68% majority.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{Bar chart\n| title      = Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by gender\n| data_max   = 10,000\n| label3  = Female | data3  = 9,983  | comment3  =  50.11%\n| label4  = Male   | data4  = 9,938  | comment4  =  49.89%\n}}\n|{{Bar chart\n| title      = Population of Ulcinj (town) by gender\n| data_max   = 5500\n| label3  = Female | data3  = 5,441  | comment3  =  50.82%\n| label4  = Male   | data4  = 5,266  | comment4  =  49.18%\n}}\n|}\n\n=== Ethnicity, language and religion ===\nThe majority ethnic group in Ulcinj are [[Albanians]]. The largest spoken language is [[Albanian language|Albanian]].\n\n'''Population by ethnicity (2011 census):'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by ethnicity\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanians|yellow|70.66}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrins|red|12.44}}\n{{bar percent|Bosniaks|lightgreen|6.12}}\n{{bar percent|Serbs|blue|5.75}}\n{{bar percent|Roma/Egyptians|brown|1.17}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|3.86}}\n}}\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (town) by ethnicity\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanians|yellow|60.89}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrins|red|17.07}}\n{{bar percent|Serbs|blue|8.54}}\n{{bar percent|Bosniaks|lightgreen|7.30}}\n{{bar percent|Roma/Egyptians|brown|2.12}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|4.08}}\n}}\n|}\n'''Population by mother tongue (2011 census):'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by mother tongue\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanian|yellow|72.04}}\n{{bar percent|Serbian|blue|11.97}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrin|red|10.73}}\n{{bar percent|Bosnian|lightgreen|1.04}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|4.22}}\n}}\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (town) by mother tongue\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanian|yellow|62.29}}\n{{bar percent|Serbian|blue|18.18}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrin|red|13.73}}\n{{bar percent|Bosnian|lightgreen|1.19}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|4.61}}\n}}\n|}\n'''Population by religion (2011 census):'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by religion\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Muslims|green|71.82}}\n{{bar percent|Orthodox|blue|14.88}}\n{{bar percent|Catholics|red|11.02}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|2.28}}\n}}\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (town) by religion\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Muslims|green|68.15}}\n{{bar percent|Orthodox|blue|22.65}}\n{{bar percent|Catholics|red|6.45}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|2.75}}\n}}\n|}\n\n== International relations ==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Montenegro}}\n\n===Twin towns &ndash; Sister cities===\nUlcinj is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{Plainlist|\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} \u2013 '''[[Liesing]]''' <small>(23rd district of [[Vienna]])</small>, [[Austria]] </small><ref name=\"uom.me\" /><ref>[http://m.wien.gv.at/politik/international/netzwerke/bezirkspartnerschaften.html Bezirkspartnerschaften der Stadt Wien]</ref>\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} \u2013 '''[[Lukavac]]''', [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] <small></small><ref>[http://lukavac.ba/opcina-lukavac/saradnja-opcina-lukavac-i-ulcinj/ \u201cBratimljenje\u201d Lukavca i Ulcinja od posebne va\u017enosti za privrednu saradnju] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518100042/http://lukavac.ba/opcina-lukavac/saradnja-opcina-lukavac-i-ulcinj/ |date=2015-05-18 }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} \u2013 '''[[Stari Grad, Sarajevo]]''', [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] <small></small><ref name=\"uom.me\" /><ref>[http://www.starigrad.ba/bs2/vijest.php?id=90 POTPISAN SPORAZUM O SARADNJI OP\u0160TINA/OP\u0106INA ULCINJ I STARI GRAD SARAJEVO] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518090006/http://www.starigrad.ba/bs2/vijest.php?id=90 |date=2015-05-18 }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Kosovo}} \u2013 '''[[Prizren]]''', [[Kosovo]]\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} \u2013 '''[[Uzhhorod]]''', [[Ukraine]]<ref name=\"uom.me\">[http://www.uom.co.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bratimljenje-m2-3.pdf Bratimljenje gradova Crne Gore]</ref>\n}}\n||\n{{Plainlist|\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} \u2013 '''[[Berat]]''', [[Albania]]<ref name=\"uom.me\" />\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} \u2013 '''[[Durr\u00ebs]]''', [[Albania]]<ref name=\"uom.me\" />\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} \u2013 '''[[Serik]]''', [[Turkey]] <small></small><ref>[http://ul-info.com/vizita-neser-binjakezimi-i-ulqinit-dhe-serikut/ Vizita: NES\u00cbR BINJAK\u00cbZIMI I ULQINIT DHE SERIKUT]</ref><ref>[http://www.antalyagazetesi.com.tr/6652-guncel-ulcinjli-yeni-kardesler-serikten-memnun-kaldi.html Ulcinj\u2019li yeni karde\u015fler Serik\u2019ten memnun kald\u0131] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083204/http://www.antalyagazetesi.com.tr/6652-guncel-ulcinjli-yeni-kardesler-serikten-memnun-kaldi.html |date=2015-05-18 }}</ref><ref>[http://ul-info.com/ceremonia-ne-serik-nenshkruhet-protokolli-per-binjakezim/ Ceremonia n\u00eb Serik: N\u00cbNSHKRUHET PROTOKOLLI P\u00cbR BINJAK\u00cbZIM]</ref>\n}}\n|}\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Ulcinj old town.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Ulcinj Castle|old town of Ulcinj]]]]\nUlcinj is a tourist destination in summer. In January 2010, the [[New York Times]] named ranked the south coast region of Montenegro, featuring [[Velika Plaza]], [[Ada Bojana]], and the [[Hotel Mediteran]], as one of \"The Top 31 Places to Go in 2010\".<ref>{{Cite news|ref=harv |last=Williams  |first=Gisela |date=7 January 2010 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/10/travel/10places.html?pagewanted=2&ref=travel |title=The 31 Places to Go in 2010: 24. Montenegro |newspaper=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Ulcinj is still undiscovered by many travelers from larger countries, repeat tourists and an increasing amount of first-time visitors make it a hot spot for vacationers between the months of May and September. It is most famous for its sandy beaches.{{fact|date=March 2019}} The most valuable resource of the Ulcinj riviera is [[Velika pla\u017ea]] (Albanian: Plazha e Madhe, English: Long Beach), which is a {{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=on}} long stretch of sandy beach and the longest beach on the Montenegrin coast. There is a small pebble beach called [[Ladies Beach, Ulcinj|Ladies Beach]] which folk tradition holds to have qualities conducive to fertility. \n\nThere is also a beach called ''[[Mala Pla\u017ea]]'' (Albanian: Plazha e Vog\u00ebl, English: Small Beach) which is much smaller in size, but is located in the centre of town and very popular with visitors. \"The Korzo\", as it is called by locals, is a [[promenade]] which separates a street lined with coffee shops from Mala pla\u017ea. At night during the summer months, the Korzo is pedestrianised and families and young people gather. There are many more less known smaller beaches that serve as get-aways from the main tourist areas. Ulcinj has also a large number of religious buildings like [[mosques]], [[T\u00fcrbe|tyrbes]] and [[Church (building)|churches]], including: [[Pasha's Mosque]], [[Sailors' Mosque]] and St. Nicholas' Church.\n\nUlcinj's old town is a well preserved [[castle]]-looking community that is left over from medieval times. The old town sits atop a mountain overlooking the shore and is a tourist attraction on its own. [[Ada Bojana]] (Albanian: ''Buna'') is popular among foreign tourists from [[Western Europe]] for its peace and atmosphere.{{fact|date=March 2019}} A large [[naturist]] campsite is located in Ada Bojana. [[Lake \u0160as|\u0160a\u0161ko lake]] and Ulcinj's salt pond are visited by birdwatchers, because Ulcinj and its surroundings are major resting points for over 200 bird species on their migration paths. There are numerous caf\u00e9s, discos, and bars that dot the city that are usually filled to capacity throughout the summer. The majority of tourists that visit Ulcinj are [[Albanians]], Serbians, Croatians, Bosnians, Slovenians, Macedonians, Russians, Ukrainians, and other Europeans.\n{{wide image|Montenegrin South Coast banner.jpg|1000px|Ulcinj Panorama}}\n\n== Education ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"center\" | Montenegrin name\n!align=\"center\" | Albanian name\n!align=\"center\" | Location\n!align=\"center\" | Language(s)\n|-\n|align=\"left\" colspan=4 |'''Elementary schools'''\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Bo\u0161ko Strugar\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore  ''\"Boshko Strugar\"''\n|Ulcinj\n| [[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]] & [[Albanian language|Albanian]]\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Mar\u0161al Tito\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore ''\"Marshal Tito\"''\n|Ulcinj\n| Montenegrin & Albanian\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Bedri Elezaga\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore ''\"Bedri Elezaga\"''\n|Vladimir\n| Albanian\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Marko Nuculovi\u0107\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore ''\"Mark Nuculloviq\"''\n|Donji \u0160toj\n| Montenegrin & Albanian\n|-\n|align=\"left\" colspan=4 |'''High schools'''\n|-\n|Srednja mje\u0161ovita \u0161kola ''\"Bratstvo i jedinstvo\"''\n|Shkolla e Mesme e Kombinuar  ''\"V\u00ebllaz\u00ebrim Bashkim\"''\n|Ulcinj\n| Montenegrin & Albanian\n|-\n|Gimnazija ''\"Drita\"''\n|Gjimnazi ''\"Drita\"''\n|Ulcinj\n|Albanian\n|}\n\n== Sports and recreation==\nThe Ulcinj \"south coast\" region is well known for its active sports, recreation possibilities and hunting . Kitesurfing at [[Ada Bojana]], all manner of water sports at [[Velika pla\u017ea]], scuba diving among wrecks and sunken cities, mountain biking, hiking, orienteering, cycling through the olive groves at [[Valdanos]], long walks along the pristine beaches of the south coast of Montenegro, even deep sea fishing on the Adriatic, lake fishing at [[Lake Skadar]], and river fishing in [[Ada Bojana]],  Due to the fact that the favorable habitat for wild life, has excellent conditions of hunting tourism.This place is the haven of omithological (gourmand) hunting in [[Re\u010d]] and Shenkol most common wildlife are [[woodcock]], [[Hare]], [[Wild boar]], and [[ducks]].\n\n'''List of sport clubs in Ulcinj:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"center\" colspan=2|Name\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=2| Sport\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=2| Competing\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=2| Founded\n|-\n!align=\"center\" | [[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]] name\n!align=\"center\" | [[Albanian language|Albanian]] name\n|-\n|[[FK Otrant|Fudbalski klub ''\"Otrant\"'']]\n|Klubi Fudbolistik ''\"Otrant\"''\n|[[Association football|Football]]\n|[[Montenegrin Second League]]\n|1921\n|-\n|[[KK Ulcinj|Ko\u0161arka\u0161ki klub ''\"Ulcinj\"'']]\n|Klubi i Basketbollit ''\"Ulcinj\"''\n|[[Basketball]]\n|[[Montenegrin Basketball League]]\n|1976\n|-\n|[[RK Ulcinj]]\n|Klubi i Hendbollit ''\"Ulcinj\"''\n|[[Team handball|Handball]]\n|[[Montenegrin First League of Men's Handball]]\n|\n|-\n|Teniski klub ''\"Bellevue\"''\n|Klubi i Tenisit ''\"Bellevue\"''\n|[[Tennis]]\n|\n|2009\n|-\n|Omladinski fudbalski klub ''\"Federal\"''\n|Klubi Futbolistik Rinor ''\"Federall\"''\n|[[Association football|Football]]\n|South Region League\n|2007\n|-\n|Karate klub ''\"Champions\"''\n|Klubi i Karates ''\"Champions\"''\n|[[Karate]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|Karate Klub ''\"Ulcinj\"''\n|Klubi i Karates ''\"Ulqini\"''\n|[[Karate]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|Stonoteniski Klub ''\"Valdanos\"''\n|Klubi i Ping Pongut ''\"Valdanos\"''\n|[[Table Tennis]]\n|Cadet,Junior,Senior Montenegrin League\n|2012\n|}\n\n== Climate ==\nUlcinj has a [[mediterranean climate]] (''Csa''). Winters are cool and very rainy, and summers are hot and humid with possible afternoon thunder showers. Unlike [[Podgorica]] temperatures very rarely exceed {{convert|35|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} and seldom drop below {{convert|0|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Ulcinj, [[Montenegro]]\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n\n|Jan high C = 10.7\n|Feb high C = 11.6\n|Mar high C = 14.7\n|Apr high C = 17.9\n|May high C = 22.1\n|Jun high C = 26.2\n|Jul high C = 29.2\n|Aug high C = 29.2\n|Sep high C = 26.1\n|Oct high C = 21.3\n|Nov high C = 16.1\n|Dec high C = 12.1\n\n|Jan mean C = 7.1\n|Feb mean C = 7.9\n|Mar mean C = 10.6\n|Apr mean C = 13.6\n|May mean C = 17.9\n|Jun mean C = 21.7\n|Jul mean C = 24.4\n|Aug mean C = 24.2\n|Sep mean C = 21.2\n|Oct mean C = 16.8\n|Nov mean C = 12.2\n|Dec mean C = 8.6\n\n|Jan low C = 4.1\n|Feb low C = 4.7\n|Mar low C = 7.2\n|Apr low C = 10.1\n|May low C = 14.1\n|Jun low C = 17.8\n|Jul low C = 20.2\n|Aug low C = 20.1\n|Sep low C = 17.3\n|Oct low C = 13.1\n|Nov low C = 9.0\n|Dec low C = 5.6 \n\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 149.3\n|Feb precipitation mm = 137.9\n|Mar precipitation mm = 115.7\n|Apr precipitation mm = 115.2\n|May precipitation mm = 66.9\n|Jun precipitation mm = 46.5\n|Jul precipitation mm = 25.2\n|Aug precipitation mm = 48.6\n|Sep precipitation mm = 84.6\n|Oct precipitation mm = 148.2\n|Nov precipitation mm = 173.7\n|Dec precipitation mm = 146.1\n\n|unit precipitation days = 0.1 mm\n|Jan precipitation days = 12\n|Feb precipitation days = 12\n|Mar precipitation days = 12\n|Apr precipitation days = 12\n|May precipitation days = 8\n|Jun precipitation days = 7\n|Jul precipitation days = 4\n|Aug precipitation days = 4\n|Sep precipitation days = 7\n|Oct precipitation days = 10\n|Nov precipitation days = 13\n|Dec precipitation days = 12\n\n|Jan sun = 121.3\n|Feb sun = 126.8\n|Mar sun = 170.5\n|Apr sun = 202.3\n|May sun = 263.7\n|Jun sun = 299.2\n|Jul sun = 349.9\n|Aug sun = 319.6\n|Sep sun = 255.8\n|Oct sun = 195.7\n|Nov sun = 134.6\n|Dec sun = 118.2\n\n|Jan humidity = 66\n|Feb humidity = 64\n|Mar humidity = 66\n|Apr humidity = 70\n|May humidity = 71\n|Jun humidity = 69\n|Jul humidity = 62\n|Aug humidity = 63\n|Sep humidity = 66\n|Oct humidity = 67\n|Nov humidity = 69\n|Dec humidity = 67\n\n|source 1 = Hydrological and Meteorological Service of Montenegro<ref name=HMSM>{{cite web\n|url = http://195.66.163.23/misc.php?text=126&sektor=1\n|title = Climate: Ulcinj\n|publisher = Hydrological and Meteorological Service of Montenegro\n|accessdate = May 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|date = May 2018}}\n\n== Transport ==\n [[File:Spitali.JPG|thumb|Community Health Centre in Ulcinj]]\nUlcinj is connected with the rest of Montenegro by two-lane highway. It is connected with other coastal towns by the [[Adriatic Motorway]]. Reaching inland is made possible by detouring from the Adriatic Motorway at [[Budva]] or [[Sutomore]] (through the [[Sozina tunnel]]).\n\nAs of today, there are no airports in the city of Ulcinj. However, nearby airports in [[Tivat Airport|Tivat]] and [[Podgorica Airport|Podgorica]] are both around {{convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}} away. There are regular flights to [[Belgrade]] and [[Z\u00fcrich]] from Tivat. Podgorica Airport has regular flights to major [[Europe]]an destinations throughout the year. Many tourists traveling to Ulcinj from abroad arrive to the city from the airport in Tivat due to its recent renovations and general ease of navigation.\n\n== Notable locals ==\nNotable people who lived in Ulcinj or its surroundings include :\n*[[\u0110ura\u0111 II Bal\u0161i\u0107]], Lord of [[Principality of Zeta|Zeta]] from 1385 to 1403, member of the [[Bal\u0161i\u0107 noble family]]. \n*[[Jelena Bal\u0161i\u0107]], daughter of [[Lazar of Serbia]], author of [[Gori\u010dki zbornik]], first woman writer in South Slavs\n*[[Gjon Buzuku]], Catholic priest who wrote the first known printed book in Albanian\n*[[Pjet\u00ebr Gjoka]], actor and People's Artist of Albania\n*[[John VIII, Archbishop of Antivari|John VIII or Giovanni Bruni]], archbishop of Bar, 1551-1571\n*[[Adrian Lulgjuraj]], Montenegrin-Albanian singer\n*[[Ndoc Martini]], painter\n*[[Alex Rudaj]], Albanian-American mobster\n*[[Lika Ceni]], Captain and Pirate Commander\n*[[Rade Tovladijac]], Serbian comic book artist\n*[[Mark Gjonaj]], Albanian-American politician\n*[[Mujo Ulqinaku]], Albanian officer and a People's Hero of Albania\n*[[Sabbatai Zevi]], \u0130zmir born mystic, founder of the Jewish [[Sabbatean]] movement\n* [[Andrej Nikolaidis]], Montenegrin writer\n*[[Cafo Beg Ulqini]], Leader of Second League of Prizren and Knight of the Order of Skandebeg<ref>http://www.visit-ulcinj.com/blog/2016/04/20/nishani-dekoron-cafo-beg-ulqinin-titullin-kalores-urdhrit-te-skenderbeut/</ref>\n* [[Bo\u017eidar \u0110ura\u0161kovi\u0107]], Montenegrin athlete, gold medal winner at Mediterranean Games\n* [[Vladimir Mihailovi\u0107]], Montenegrin basketball national team player\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ulcinj}}\n{{MontenegroCities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ulcinj}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Ulcinj Municipality]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies in Illyria]]\n[[Category:Ulcinj| ]]\n[[Category:Geg\u00ebri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox settlement-->\n| native_name                     = \u0423\u043b\u0446\u0438\u045a<br>Ulqin\n| name                            = Ulcinj\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of cities in Montenegro|Town]] and [[Municipalities of Montenegro|municipality]]\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{MNE}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Municipalities of Montenegro|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Ulcinj Municipality]]\n| timezone                        = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset                      = +1\n| image_skyline                   = Ulcinj, Montenegro - Sept. 2010.jpg\n| map_caption                     = Location of Ulcinj, Montenegro.\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = +2\n| population_as_of                = 2011 census\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Loro Nrekiq\n| leader_party                    = [[Democratic Party of Socialists of Montenegro|DPS]]\n| leader_title1                   = Ruling&nbsp;party\n| area_total_km2                  = 255\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_blank1               = 19,921\n| population_blank1_title         = Municipality\n| population_density_km2          = 79.47\n| population_urban                = 10,707\n| population_rural                = 9,214\n| population_demonym              = Ulcinjani<br />Ulqinak\u00eb\n| parts                           = 39\n| parts_type                      = Settlements\n| established_date                = 5th century BC\n| pushpin_map                     = Montenegro\n| pushpin_label_position          = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location of Ulcinj\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|41.92|19.20|region:ME|display=inline,title}}\n| area_code_type                  = [[Telephone numbers in Montenegro|Area code]]\n| area_code                       = +382&nbsp;30\n| blank1_info_sec1                = UL\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Vehicle registration plates of Montenegro|Car&nbsp;plates]]\n| postal_code_type                = [[List of postal codes in Montenegro|Postal code]]\n| postal_code                     = 85360\n| blank_info_sec1                 = ME-20\n| blank_name_sec1                 = [[ISO 3166-2:ME|ISO 3166-2&nbsp;code]]\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.ul-gov.me|Official Website}}\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_shield                    = Coat of Arms of Ulcinj.svg\n| shield_alt                      = [[Coat of arms of Ulcinj|Coat of arms]]\n}}\n\n'''Ulcinj''' ([[Montenegrin Cyrillic]]: \u0423\u043b\u0446\u0438\u045a, {{IPA-sh|\u01d4lt\u0361si\u0272|pron}}; [[Albanian language|Albanian]]: ''Ulqin'' or ''Ulqini'') is a town on the southern coast of [[Montenegro]] and the capital of [[Ulcinj Municipality]]. It has an urban population of 10,707 (2011), the majority being [[Albanians]].\n\nAs one of the oldest settlements in the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic coast]], it was founded in 5th century BC. It was captured by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] in 163 BC from the [[Illyrians]]. With the division of the [[Roman Empire]], it became part of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. It was known as a base for [[piracy]].\n\nDuring the [[Middle Ages]] it was under [[South Slavs|South Slavic]] rule for a few centuries. In 1405 it became part of [[Republic of Venice]] and in 1571 part of [[Ottoman Empire]]. Ulcinj was ceded to the [[Principality of Montenegro]] in 1878. It is a former medieval Catholic bishopric and remains a Latin [[titular see]].\n\nUlcinj is a destination for tourists, because of its [[Velika Pla\u017ea|Long Beach]], [[Lake \u0160as]], [[Ada Bojana|Ada Bojana Island]] and for its two-millennia-old [[Ulcinj Castle]]. Ulcinj is also the centre of the [[Albanians in Montenegro|Albanian community in Montenegro]].\n\n== Names ==\nEarly historian [[Livy]] (59 BC\u2013AD 17) mentioned it,<ref name=\"Mijovi\u01071970\">{{cite book|author=Pavle Mijovi\u0107|title=Tragom drevnih kultura Crne Gore|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ef0bAAAAMAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Grafi\u010dki zavod|page=35}}</ref> as did [[Pliny the Elder]] (23\u201379),<ref name=\"PraschnikerSchober1976\">{{cite book|author1=C. Praschniker|author2=A. Schober|title=Arch?ologische Forschungen in Albanien und Montenegro|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DO4JAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA82|year=1976|publisher=\u0420\u0438\u043f\u043e\u043b \u041a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043a|isbn=978-5-87379-103-3|pages=82\u2013}}</ref> who mentioned it as ''Olcinium'', its old name ''Colchinium'', \"founded by [settlers from] [[Colchis]]\" (Olchinium quod antea Colchinium dictum est a Colchis conditum).<ref name=\"PraschnikerSchober1976\"/> [[Ptolemy]] (90\u2013168) mentions the city as Greek ''Oulkinion'' (\u039f\u03c5\u03bb\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd).<ref>{{cite book|title=Claudii Ptolemaei Geographia edidit Carolus Fridericus Augustus Nobbe|volume=1|chapter=16|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BKJA_GDRGT4C|year=1843|publisher=sumptibus et typis Caroli Tauchnitii|page=134}}</ref> Although the ancient writers preferred a connection with Cholchis, the name of the settlement appears to be connected with the [[Albanian language|Albanian]] word ''ujk'' or ''ulk'' (meaning [[wolf]] in [[English language|English]]),<ref name=\"Wilkes244\">{{cite book|last=Wilkes|first=John|title=The Illyrians|year=1992|publisher=Wiley|isbn=9780631146711|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=l8q0QgAACAAJ&dq=Wilkes%20the%20illyrians&source=gbs_book_other_versions|pages=244|ref=harv}} \"Names of individuals peoples may have been formed in a similar fashion, Taulantii from \u2018swallow\u2019 (cf. the Albanian tallandushe) or Erchelei the \u2018eel-men\u2019 and Chelidoni the \u2018snail-men\u2019. The name of the Delmatae appears connected with the Albanian word for \u2018sheep\u2019 delm\u00eb) and the Dardanians with for \u2018pear\u2019 (dardh\u00eb). Some place names appear to have similar derivations, including Olcinium (Ulcinj from \u2018wolf\u2019 (ukas), although the ancients preferred a connection with Cholchis.\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|last= Birnbaum|first=Henrik|last2=Puhvel|first2=Jaan|title=Ancient Indo-European Dialects|chapter=The Position of Albanian|year=1963|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=|url=https://books.google.it/books?id=5pCBRsfJMv8C&vq|page=108|ref=harv}}</ref> from [[Proto-Albanian language|Proto-Albanian]] ''*(w)ulka'', from [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] ''*w\u013a\u0325k\u02b7os''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Orel|first=Vladimir|title=Albanian etymological dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yJQYAQAAIAAJ&dq|year=1998|publisher=Brill|isbn=9004110240|p=484}}</ref> The name, through Late (Vulgar) Roman, became [[Middle Latin]] '''Ulcinium''', {{lang-it|Dulcigno}} ({{IPA-it|dul\u02c8t\u0283i\u0272\u0272o|pron}}), [[Slavic languages|Slavic]]: ''Ulcinj'', {{lang-sq|Ulqin}} or ''Ulqini'' and {{lang-tr|\u00dclg\u00fcn}}.\n\n== Geography ==\n\n=== Neighbourhoods ===\n*''\u00c7arshia'' (mn. ''\u010car\u0161ija''), is a [[neighborhood]] and town centre which connects the old and new parts (neighbourhoods). In 2009 it was reconstructed, with the [[asphalt concrete|asphalt]] being changed into [[sett (paving)|sett]] and the water and electrical system were changed. The neighbourhood has some 200 shops. It has an oriental atmosphere. There are two [[mosques]] located in this area, the [[Namazgjahu Mosque]] and [[Kryepazari Mosque]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Antiquity ===\nUlcinj is an ancient seaport.<ref name= Rellie>{{cite book |title= Montenegro|last= Rellie |first= Annalisa |year=2012 |publisher= The Globe Pequot Press Inc |location= Bradt Travel Guides Ltd, IDC House, The Vale, Chalfront St Peter, Bucks SL9 9RZ, England|isbn=978 1 84162 381 8  |pages=207\u2013208 |url= https://books.google.com.au/books?id=L0Apj11ifqUC&pg=PA206&dq=Ulcinj&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GrbBUZ2lLqWkigK9l4DADA&ved=0CFcQ6AEwBw|accessdate=2013-06-20}}</ref> The wider area of Ulcinj has been inhabited since the [[Bronze Age]], based on dating of [[Illyrians|Illyrian]] tombs (tumuli) found in the village of [[Zogaj, Shkod\u00ebr|Zogaj]], in the vicinity of Ulcinj. The town is believed to have been founded in the 5th century BC by colonists from [[Colchis]], as mentioned in the 3rd century BC poem by [[Apollonius of Rhodes]]. Illyrians lived in the region at the time as there are traces of immense [[Cyclopean walls]] still visible in the old Citadel.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nAll the way in the pre-medieval period, Ulcinj was known as one of the pirate capitals of the [[Adriatic Sea]]. This is also seen during the later period of [[Illyrian Kingdom]]. Inhabitants of Ulcinj were known before time of [[Christ]], especially from 20 BC to around 300 AD, to be very confrontational to those who were foreigners to their land; they were especially meticulous about border disputes as well.\n\n=== Roman ===\n[[File:Roman_Doclea.gif|thumb|Roman Doclea]]\nIn 168 BC, during the [[Third Illyrian War]], Olcinium broke with [[Gentius]] and defected to the Romans ([[Livy]] 45:26:2). Under Roman rule the town received the status of ''oppidum civium Romanorum'' (settlement of Roman citizens), only to be later granted ''[[municipium]]'' (independent town) status. A section of their re-fortification can be distinguished from the Illyrio-Greek by the rustication of the walls.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nThe ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea|Periplus Maris Erythraei]]'' names several Indian ports [[Indian_maritime_history#Early_Common_Era\u2014High_Middle_Ages|from where large ships sailed]] in an easterly direction to ''[[Ulcinj|Khruse]]'' (Kru\u010de - seaside village in Ulcinj).<ref>Donkin, Robin A. (2003), ''Between East and West: The Moluccas and the Traffic in Spices Up to the Arrival of Europeans'', Diane Publishing Company, {{ISBN|0-87169-248-1}}, page. 64</ref> \n\nAfter the division of the Roman Empire, Ulcinj became a part of the Byzantine province of [[Prevalis]] and the population converted to Christianity. From Medieval times, and quiet likely earlier, it was regarded as an important trading and maritime center and still maintained the status of city autonomy.<ref name= Rellie/> From circa 820, the city was the see of a [[Diocese of Ulcinj]], which was only suppressed in 1532, and would be revived as a Latin [[titular bishopric]].\n\n=== Medieval period and South Slavic rule ===\nIn the 9th century, it was in the [[Dyrrhachium (theme)|Dyrrhachium theme]], a military governorate of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. In 1010, ''Tsar'' [[Samuel of Bulgaria]] (r. 997-1014\u2020) failed to conquer the town during the [[Byzantine-Bulgarian Wars#Sviatoslav.27s invasion and the Byzantine conquest of Bulgaria|war against the Byzantines]].\n \nBy 1040, ''archon'' [[Vojislav of Duklja|Stefan Vojislav]] of [[Duklja]] conquered the region. In 1183, [[Serbian Grand Principality|Serbian Prince]] [[Stefan Nemanja]] conquered Olcinium and the town prospered as one of the most significant coastal towns. Ulcinj remained in Nemanji\u0107 hands in their [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Kingdom]] and [[Serbian Empire|Empire]], and after the death of [[Emperor Du\u0161an]] (r. 1331-1355\u2020), the region, known as ''Lower [[Lordship of Zeta|Zeta]]'', was under the supervision of ''gospodin'' [[\u017darko (nobleman)|\u017darko]], a ''voivode'' of Emperor [[Uro\u0161 the Weak]] until his death in 1360. \u017darko's lands were then held by the [[Bal\u0161i\u0107]] family. Under Bal\u0161i\u0107 control, Ulcinj continued to be an important town and also [[Mint (coin)|minted coins]]. The Bal\u0161i\u0107 Tower in the upper part of the Old Town was built by the [[Bal\u0161i\u0107 noble family]] in the late 14th century.\n\n=== Venetian and Ottoman rule ===\n[[File:Dulcingo Pinargenti 1573.jpg|thumb|Map of Dulcigno (now Ulcinj) in 1573 by Simon Pinargenti]]\nIn 1405 the Venetians conquered the town. Under Venetian control, the city was renamed ''Dulcigno'' in [[Italian language|Italian]], and it was incorporated in the [[Albania Veneta]]. The Venetians maintained control until 1571, when the [[Ottoman Turks]] conquered Dulcigno with the help of [[Barbary pirates]], who didn't leave the town after conquering. It remained within the Ottoman domain for over 300 years, during which time its far-reaching reputation as a lair of pirates was established.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nIn the 17th century a self-proclaimed Jewish [[Messiah]] named [[Sabbatai Zevi]] caused turmoil throughout the Turkish Empire with his evangelizing, which attracted thousands of followers. He was eventually captured and exiled to Ulcinj in 1666, where he died quietly ten years later. He was buried in the courtyard of a Muslim house which is still preserved as a mausoleum; along with two Jewish altars in the Bal\u0161ic Tower.<ref name= Rellie/>\n\nIn 1867, Ulcinj became a [[township|kaza]] of the [[Sanjak of Scutari|\u0130\u015fkodra sanjak]] of [[Rumeli]] veyalet. After the [[Congress of Berlin]] in 1878, borders between Montenegro and the Ottoman Empire were redrawn, with [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]] and [[Gusinje]] being ceded to Montenegro. But Muslim Albanian resistance prevented the Montenegrins from taking over Plav and Gusinje, so the Great Powers in 1880 decided to reverse the territorial transfer and offered Ulcinj to Montenegro as compensation.\n\n=== 20th century to present ===\n[[File:Fish-market in Ulcinj (1908).jpg|thumb|Ulcinj fish market in 1908]]\nUlcinj became a part of the [[Kingdom of Montenegro]] from 1878 until 1918 when Montenegro was absorbed into the [[Kingdom of Serbia]] for a short time before all would be incorporated into the first of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] federations at the end of the year. Ulcinj remained within a Montenegrin entity whilst a South Slavic state had existed until 2006 when which it became part of an independent Montenegro following a referendum.\n\nDuring the 20th century, Ulcinj survived heavy declines and new ascents. Ulcinj was the second biggest town of Montenegro when it joined the kingdom in 1880. In just three decades, it backslided to 6th place for economic development and number of inhabitants (after Podgorica, Niksic, Cetinje, Tivar and Plava). During World War I Ulcinj was conquered by Austria-Hungary in 1916 and Italy on November 4, 1918,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://augusto.digitpa.gov.it/gazzette/index/download/id/1918261_PM|title=Gazzetta Ufficiale del Regno d'Italia N. 261 del 6 Novembre 1918|last=|first=|date=6 November 1918|work=Gazzetta Ufficiale del Regno d'Italia|accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> and since 1920 it was part of the Serbo-Croatian-Slovenian Kingdom, later known as the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]].\n\nAs the southernmost city of the coast of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia, Ulcinj had a strong turnaround in the 1930s with the development of the tourist industry. At that time hotels were built such as Kri\u0161tja, Republic, Jadran and Koop (later Galeb). \nWorld War II halted economic momentum. From 1941 to 1944, Ulcinj was under the Albanian administration. On November 7, 1943, Ulcinj was bombarded by Allied forces, with over 46 people  killed and many more injured. The [[Yugoslav Partisans]] took Ulcinj on November 26, 1944, and the city become part of [[Socialist Yugoslavia]]. <ref>[[#LTKU-1989|LTKU (1989)]], fq. 46</ref><ref>[http://www.cdm.me/politika/cetkovic-dps-i-forca-hoce-da-brisu-istoriju-ulcinja \u0106etkovi\u0107: DPS i Forca ho\u0107e da bri\u0161u istoriju Ulcinja]</ref><ref>[http://www.visit-ulcinj.com/blog/2014/03/19/ruzna-strana-lepote-ulcinja/ Ru\u017ena strana lepote Ulcinja]</ref>\n\nThe 1950s and 1960s marked the gratest period of economic development for Ulcinj, with the construction of a range of modern hotels in the city and the Great Plain, as well as major economic collectives (NHT \"Riviera of Ulcinj\", \"Agroulqini\", Primary Building Company, \"Otrantkomerc\", \"Ultep\" and others). In the catastrophic earthquake on April 15, 1979, the city was severely damaged, but after only a few years, with the solidarity of the citizens of entire Yugoslavia, it was quickly renovated. Ulcinj at the end of the eighties had about 40 percent of the tourist turnover in Montenegro, while two-thirds of the guests were foreign, mostly German.\n\nDuring the Kosovo War, in 1998 and 1999, thousands of Kosovo Albanians flocked to Ulcinj and its surroundings, where they were welcomed in the best possible conditions by the ethnic Albanian population of Ulcinj and the surrounding area.\n\n== Population ==\n{{Historical populations\n| 1948|4385\n| 1953|4919\n| 1961|5705\n| 1971|7459\n| 1981|9140\n| 1991|10025\n| 2003|10828\n| 2011|10707\n|footnote=\n}}\nUlcinj is the administrative centre of [[Ulcinj Municipality]], which has a population of 19,921. The town of Ulcinj itself has a population of 10,707. Ulcinj Municipality is the centre of the [[Albanians in Montenegro|Albanian community in Montenegro]]. It is one of two municipalities in Montenegro where [[Albanians]] form the majority with 70%, the other being [[Tuzi Municipality|Tuzi]] with a 68% majority.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{Bar chart\n| title      = Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by gender\n| data_max   = 10,000\n| label3  = Female | data3  = 9,983  | comment3  =  50.11%\n| label4  = Male   | data4  = 9,938  | comment4  =  49.89%\n}}\n|{{Bar chart\n| title      = Population of Ulcinj (town) by gender\n| data_max   = 5500\n| label3  = Female | data3  = 5,441  | comment3  =  50.82%\n| label4  = Male   | data4  = 5,266  | comment4  =  49.18%\n}}\n|}\n\n=== Ethnicity, language and religion ===\nThe majority ethnic group in Ulcinj are [[Albanians]]. The largest spoken language is [[Albanian language|Albanian]].\n\n'''Population by ethnicity (2011 census):'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by ethnicity\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanians|yellow|70.66}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrins|red|12.44}}\n{{bar percent|Bosniaks|lightgreen|6.12}}\n{{bar percent|Serbs|blue|5.75}}\n{{bar percent|Roma/Egyptians|brown|1.17}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|3.86}}\n}}\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (town) by ethnicity\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanians|yellow|60.89}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrins|red|17.07}}\n{{bar percent|Serbs|blue|8.54}}\n{{bar percent|Bosniaks|lightgreen|7.30}}\n{{bar percent|Roma/Egyptians|brown|2.12}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|4.08}}\n}}\n|}\n'''Population by mother tongue (2011 census):'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by mother tongue\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanian|yellow|72.04}}\n{{bar percent|Serbian|blue|11.97}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrin|red|10.73}}\n{{bar percent|Bosnian|lightgreen|1.04}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|4.22}}\n}}\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (town) by mother tongue\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Albanian|yellow|62.29}}\n{{bar percent|Serbian|blue|18.18}}\n{{bar percent|Montenegrin|red|13.73}}\n{{bar percent|Bosnian|lightgreen|1.19}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|4.61}}\n}}\n|}\n'''Population by religion (2011 census):'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (municipality) by religion\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Muslims|green|71.82}}\n{{bar percent|Orthodox|blue|14.88}}\n{{bar percent|Catholics|red|11.02}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|2.28}}\n}}\n|{{bar box\n|width=300px\n|title=Population of Ulcinj (town) by religion\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Muslims|green|68.15}}\n{{bar percent|Orthodox|blue|22.65}}\n{{bar percent|Catholics|red|6.45}}\n{{bar percent|other|gray|2.75}}\n}}\n|}\n\n== International relations ==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Montenegro}}\n\n===Twin towns &ndash; Sister cities===\nUlcinj is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{Plainlist|\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} \u2013 '''[[Liesing]]''' <small>(23rd district of [[Vienna]])</small>, [[Austria]] </small><ref name=\"uom.me\" /><ref>[http://m.wien.gv.at/politik/international/netzwerke/bezirkspartnerschaften.html Bezirkspartnerschaften der Stadt Wien]</ref>\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} \u2013 '''[[Lukavac]]''', [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] <small></small><ref>[http://lukavac.ba/opcina-lukavac/saradnja-opcina-lukavac-i-ulcinj/ \u201cBratimljenje\u201d Lukavca i Ulcinja od posebne va\u017enosti za privrednu saradnju] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518100042/http://lukavac.ba/opcina-lukavac/saradnja-opcina-lukavac-i-ulcinj/ |date=2015-05-18 }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} \u2013 '''[[Stari Grad, Sarajevo]]''', [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] <small></small><ref name=\"uom.me\" /><ref>[http://www.starigrad.ba/bs2/vijest.php?id=90 POTPISAN SPORAZUM O SARADNJI OP\u0160TINA/OP\u0106INA ULCINJ I STARI GRAD SARAJEVO] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518090006/http://www.starigrad.ba/bs2/vijest.php?id=90 |date=2015-05-18 }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Kosovo}} \u2013 '''[[Prizren]]''', [[Kosovo]]\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} \u2013 '''[[Uzhhorod]]''', [[Ukraine]]<ref name=\"uom.me\">[http://www.uom.co.me/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bratimljenje-m2-3.pdf Bratimljenje gradova Crne Gore]</ref>\n}}\n||\n{{Plainlist|\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} \u2013 '''[[Berat]]''', [[Albania]]<ref name=\"uom.me\" />\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} \u2013 '''[[Durr\u00ebs]]''', [[Albania]]<ref name=\"uom.me\" />\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} \u2013 '''[[Serik]]''', [[Turkey]] <small></small><ref>[http://ul-info.com/vizita-neser-binjakezimi-i-ulqinit-dhe-serikut/ Vizita: NES\u00cbR BINJAK\u00cbZIMI I ULQINIT DHE SERIKUT]</ref><ref>[http://www.antalyagazetesi.com.tr/6652-guncel-ulcinjli-yeni-kardesler-serikten-memnun-kaldi.html Ulcinj\u2019li yeni karde\u015fler Serik\u2019ten memnun kald\u0131] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083204/http://www.antalyagazetesi.com.tr/6652-guncel-ulcinjli-yeni-kardesler-serikten-memnun-kaldi.html |date=2015-05-18 }}</ref><ref>[http://ul-info.com/ceremonia-ne-serik-nenshkruhet-protokolli-per-binjakezim/ Ceremonia n\u00eb Serik: N\u00cbNSHKRUHET PROTOKOLLI P\u00cbR BINJAK\u00cbZIM]</ref>\n}}\n|}\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Ulcinj old town.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Ulcinj Castle|old town of Ulcinj]]]]\nUlcinj is a tourist destination in summer. In January 2010, the [[New York Times]] named ranked the south coast region of Montenegro, featuring [[Velika Plaza]], [[Ada Bojana]], and the [[Hotel Mediteran]], as one of \"The Top 31 Places to Go in 2010\".<ref>{{Cite news|ref=harv |last=Williams  |first=Gisela |date=7 January 2010 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/10/travel/10places.html?pagewanted=2&ref=travel |title=The 31 Places to Go in 2010: 24. Montenegro |newspaper=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Ulcinj is still undiscovered by many travelers from larger countries, repeat tourists and an increasing amount of first-time visitors make it a hot spot for vacationers between the months of May and September. It is most famous for its sandy beaches.{{fact|date=March 2019}} The most valuable resource of the Ulcinj riviera is [[Velika pla\u017ea]] (Albanian: Plazha e Madhe, English: Long Beach), which is a {{convert|12|km|mi|abbr=on}} long stretch of sandy beach and the longest beach on the Montenegrin coast. There is a small pebble beach called [[Ladies Beach, Ulcinj|Ladies Beach]] which folk tradition holds to have qualities conducive to fertility. \n\nThere is also a beach called ''[[Mala Pla\u017ea]]'' (Albanian: Plazha e Vog\u00ebl, English: Small Beach) which is much smaller in size, but is located in the centre of town and very popular with visitors. \"The Korzo\", as it is called by locals, is a [[promenade]] which separates a street lined with coffee shops from Mala pla\u017ea. At night during the summer months, the Korzo is pedestrianised and families and young people gather. There are many more less known smaller beaches that serve as get-aways from the main tourist areas. Ulcinj has also a large number of religious buildings like [[mosques]], [[T\u00fcrbe|tyrbes]] and [[Church (building)|churches]], including: [[Pasha's Mosque]], [[Sailors' Mosque]] and St. Nicholas' Church.\n\nUlcinj's old town is a well preserved [[castle]]-looking community that is left over from medieval times. The old town sits atop a mountain overlooking the shore and is a tourist attraction on its own. [[Ada Bojana]] (Albanian: ''Buna'') is popular among foreign tourists from [[Western Europe]] for its peace and atmosphere.{{fact|date=March 2019}} A large [[naturist]] campsite is located in Ada Bojana. [[Lake \u0160as|\u0160a\u0161ko lake]] and Ulcinj's salt pond are visited by birdwatchers, because Ulcinj and its surroundings are major resting points for over 200 bird species on their migration paths. There are numerous caf\u00e9s, discos, and bars that dot the city that are usually filled to capacity throughout the summer. The majority of tourists that visit Ulcinj are [[Albanians]], Serbians, Croatians, Bosnians, Slovenians, Macedonians, Russians, Ukrainians, and other Europeans.\n{{wide image|Montenegrin South Coast banner.jpg|1000px|Ulcinj Panorama}}\n\n== Education ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"center\" | Montenegrin name\n!align=\"center\" | Albanian name\n!align=\"center\" | Location\n!align=\"center\" | Language(s)\n|-\n|align=\"left\" colspan=4 |'''Elementary schools'''\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Bo\u0161ko Strugar\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore  ''\"Boshko Strugar\"''\n|Ulcinj\n| [[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]] & [[Albanian language|Albanian]]\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Mar\u0161al Tito\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore ''\"Marshal Tito\"''\n|Ulcinj\n| Montenegrin & Albanian\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Bedri Elezaga\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore ''\"Bedri Elezaga\"''\n|Vladimir\n| Albanian\n|-\n|Osnovna \u0161kola ''\"Marko Nuculovi\u0107\"''\n|Shkolla Fillore ''\"Mark Nuculloviq\"''\n|Donji \u0160toj\n| Montenegrin & Albanian\n|-\n|align=\"left\" colspan=4 |'''High schools'''\n|-\n|Srednja mje\u0161ovita \u0161kola ''\"Bratstvo i jedinstvo\"''\n|Shkolla e Mesme e Kombinuar  ''\"V\u00ebllaz\u00ebrim Bashkim\"''\n|Ulcinj\n| Montenegrin & Albanian\n|-\n|Gimnazija ''\"Drita\"''\n|Gjimnazi ''\"Drita\"''\n|Ulcinj\n|Albanian\n|}\n\n== Sports and recreation==\nThe Ulcinj \"south coast\" region is well known for its active sports, recreation possibilities and hunting . Kitesurfing at [[Ada Bojana]], all manner of water sports at [[Velika pla\u017ea]], scuba diving among wrecks and sunken cities, mountain biking, hiking, orienteering, cycling through the olive groves at [[Valdanos]], long walks along the pristine beaches of the south coast of Montenegro, even deep sea fishing on the Adriatic, lake fishing at [[Lake Skadar]], and river fishing in [[Ada Bojana]],  Due to the fact that the favorable habitat for wild life, has excellent conditions of hunting tourism.This place is the haven of omithological (gourmand) hunting in [[Re\u010d]] and Shenkol most common wildlife are [[woodcock]], [[Hare]], [[Wild boar]], and [[ducks]].\n\n'''List of sport clubs in Ulcinj:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"center\" colspan=2|Name\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=2| Sport\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=2| Competing\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=2| Founded\n|-\n!align=\"center\" | [[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]] name\n!align=\"center\" | [[Albanian language|Albanian]] name\n|-\n|[[FK Otrant|Fudbalski klub ''\"Otrant\"'']]\n|Klubi Fudbolistik ''\"Otrant\"''\n|[[Association football|Football]]\n|[[Montenegrin Second League]]\n|1921\n|-\n|[[KK Ulcinj|Ko\u0161arka\u0161ki klub ''\"Ulcinj\"'']]\n|Klubi i Basketbollit ''\"Ulcinj\"''\n|[[Basketball]]\n|[[Montenegrin Basketball League]]\n|1976\n|-\n|[[RK Ulcinj]]\n|Klubi i Hendbollit ''\"Ulcinj\"''\n|[[Team handball|Handball]]\n|[[Montenegrin First League of Men's Handball]]\n|\n|-\n|Teniski klub ''\"Bellevue\"''\n|Klubi i Tenisit ''\"Bellevue\"''\n|[[Tennis]]\n|\n|2009\n|-\n|Omladinski fudbalski klub ''\"Federal\"''\n|Klubi Futbolistik Rinor ''\"Federall\"''\n|[[Association football|Football]]\n|South Region League\n|2007\n|-\n|Karate klub ''\"Champions\"''\n|Klubi i Karates ''\"Champions\"''\n|[[Karate]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|Karate Klub ''\"Ulcinj\"''\n|Klubi i Karates ''\"Ulqini\"''\n|[[Karate]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|Stonoteniski Klub ''\"Valdanos\"''\n|Klubi i Ping Pongut ''\"Valdanos\"''\n|[[Table Tennis]]\n|Cadet,Junior,Senior Montenegrin League\n|2012\n|}\n\n== Climate ==\nUlcinj has a [[mediterranean climate]] (''Csa''). Winters are cool and very rainy, and summers are hot and humid with possible afternoon thunder showers. Unlike [[Podgorica]] temperatures very rarely exceed {{convert|35|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} and seldom drop below {{convert|0|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Ulcinj, [[Montenegro]]\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n\n|Jan high C = 10.7\n|Feb high C = 11.6\n|Mar high C = 14.7\n|Apr high C = 17.9\n|May high C = 22.1\n|Jun high C = 26.2\n|Jul high C = 29.2\n|Aug high C = 29.2\n|Sep high C = 26.1\n|Oct high C = 21.3\n|Nov high C = 16.1\n|Dec high C = 12.1\n\n|Jan mean C = 7.1\n|Feb mean C = 7.9\n|Mar mean C = 10.6\n|Apr mean C = 13.6\n|May mean C = 17.9\n|Jun mean C = 21.7\n|Jul mean C = 24.4\n|Aug mean C = 24.2\n|Sep mean C = 21.2\n|Oct mean C = 16.8\n|Nov mean C = 12.2\n|Dec mean C = 8.6\n\n|Jan low C = 4.1\n|Feb low C = 4.7\n|Mar low C = 7.2\n|Apr low C = 10.1\n|May low C = 14.1\n|Jun low C = 17.8\n|Jul low C = 20.2\n|Aug low C = 20.1\n|Sep low C = 17.3\n|Oct low C = 13.1\n|Nov low C = 9.0\n|Dec low C = 5.6 \n\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 149.3\n|Feb precipitation mm = 137.9\n|Mar precipitation mm = 115.7\n|Apr precipitation mm = 115.2\n|May precipitation mm = 66.9\n|Jun precipitation mm = 46.5\n|Jul precipitation mm = 25.2\n|Aug precipitation mm = 48.6\n|Sep precipitation mm = 84.6\n|Oct precipitation mm = 148.2\n|Nov precipitation mm = 173.7\n|Dec precipitation mm = 146.1\n\n|unit precipitation days = 0.1 mm\n|Jan precipitation days = 12\n|Feb precipitation days = 12\n|Mar precipitation days = 12\n|Apr precipitation days = 12\n|May precipitation days = 8\n|Jun precipitation days = 7\n|Jul precipitation days = 4\n|Aug precipitation days = 4\n|Sep precipitation days = 7\n|Oct precipitation days = 10\n|Nov precipitation days = 13\n|Dec precipitation days = 12\n\n|Jan sun = 121.3\n|Feb sun = 126.8\n|Mar sun = 170.5\n|Apr sun = 202.3\n|May sun = 263.7\n|Jun sun = 299.2\n|Jul sun = 349.9\n|Aug sun = 319.6\n|Sep sun = 255.8\n|Oct sun = 195.7\n|Nov sun = 134.6\n|Dec sun = 118.2\n\n|Jan humidity = 66\n|Feb humidity = 64\n|Mar humidity = 66\n|Apr humidity = 70\n|May humidity = 71\n|Jun humidity = 69\n|Jul humidity = 62\n|Aug humidity = 63\n|Sep humidity = 66\n|Oct humidity = 67\n|Nov humidity = 69\n|Dec humidity = 67\n\n|source 1 = Hydrological and Meteorological Service of Montenegro<ref name=HMSM>{{cite web\n|url = http://195.66.163.23/misc.php?text=126&sektor=1\n|title = Climate: Ulcinj\n|publisher = Hydrological and Meteorological Service of Montenegro\n|accessdate = May 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|date = May 2018}}\n\n== Transport ==\n [[File:Spitali.JPG|thumb|Community Health Centre in Ulcinj]]\nUlcinj is connected with the rest of Montenegro by two-lane highway. It is connected with other coastal towns by the [[Adriatic Motorway]]. Reaching inland is made possible by detouring from the Adriatic Motorway at [[Budva]] or [[Sutomore]] (through the [[Sozina tunnel]]).\n\nAs of today, there are no airports in the city of Ulcinj. However, nearby airports in [[Tivat Airport|Tivat]] and [[Podgorica Airport|Podgorica]] are both around {{convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}} away. There are regular flights to [[Belgrade]] and [[Z\u00fcrich]] from Tivat. Podgorica Airport has regular flights to major [[Europe]]an destinations throughout the year. Many tourists traveling to Ulcinj from abroad arrive to the city from the airport in Tivat due to its recent renovations and general ease of navigation.\n\n== Notable locals ==\nNotable people who lived in Ulcinj or its surroundings include :\n*[[\u0110ura\u0111 II Bal\u0161i\u0107]], Lord of [[Principality of Zeta|Zeta]] from 1385 to 1403, member of the [[Bal\u0161i\u0107 noble family]]. \n*[[Jelena Bal\u0161i\u0107]], daughter of [[Lazar of Serbia]], author of [[Gori\u010dki zbornik]], first woman writer in South Slavs\n*[[Gjon Buzuku]], Catholic priest who wrote the first known printed book in Albanian\n*[[Pjet\u00ebr Gjoka]], actor and People's Artist of Albania\n*[[John VIII, Archbishop of Antivari|John VIII or Giovanni Bruni]], archbishop of Bar, 1551-1571\n*[[Adrian Lulgjuraj]], Montenegrin-Albanian singer\n*[[Ndoc Martini]], painter\n*[[Alex Rudaj]], Albanian-American mobster\n*[[Lika Ceni]], Captain and Pirate Commander\n*[[Rade Tovladijac]], Serbian comic book artist\n*[[Mark Gjonaj]], Albanian-American politician\n*[[Mujo Ulqinaku]], Albanian officer and a People's Hero of Albania\n*[[Sabbatai Zevi]], \u0130zmir born mystic, founder of the Jewish [[Sabbatean]] movement\n* [[Andrej Nikolaidis]], Montenegrin writer\n*[[Cafo Beg Ulqini]], Leader of Second League of Prizren and Knight of the Order of Skandebeg<ref>http://www.visit-ulcinj.com/blog/2016/04/20/nishani-dekoron-cafo-beg-ulqinin-titullin-kalores-urdhrit-te-skenderbeut/</ref>\n* [[Bo\u017eidar \u0110ura\u0161kovi\u0107]], Montenegrin athlete, gold medal winner at Mediterranean Games\n* [[Vladimir Mihailovi\u0107]], Montenegrin basketball national team player\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ulcinj}}\n{{MontenegroCities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ulcinj}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Ulcinj Municipality]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies in Illyria]]\n[[Category:Ulcinj| ]]\n[[Category:Geg\u00ebri]]\n", "name_user": "Crazydude1912", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulcinj"}
{"title_page": "Margit Feldman", "text_new": "{{short description|Hungarian-American public speaker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Margit Buchhalter Feldman<!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image              = Margit_Feldman.png<!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Feldman in 2009\n| birth_name         = Margit Buchhalter<!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1929|06|12}}<ref name=\"Siemaszko\">{{cite news |last1=Siemaszko |first1=Corky |title=Coronavirus kills 90-year-old Holocaust survivor |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/holocaust-survivor-who-shared-her-story-students-dies-coronavirus-n1185701 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Budapest]], Hungary<ref name=\"Bella\">{{cite news |last1=Bella |first1=Timothy |title=Holocaust survivor dies of the coronavirus 75 years after she was liberated from concentration camp |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/04/17/holocaust-survivor-coronavirus/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|14|1929|06|12}}<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n| death_place        = [[Somerset, New Jersey|Somerset]], [[New Jersey]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = Complications related to [[COVID-19]]<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/>\n| nationality        = [[Hungarian-American]]\n| citizenship        = United States\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Public speaker<Br/>Educator<Br/>Activist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Holocaust survivor]]\n| notable_works      = \n| spouse             = Harvey Feldman (1953\u20132020)\n| children           = 2\n}}\n'''Margit Buchhalter Feldman''' (June 12, 1929&nbsp;\u2013 April 14, 2020) was a Hungarian-American public speaker, educator, activist, and [[Holocaust survivor]]. Feldman and her family were placed in a concentration camp in 1944, where her parents were immediately killed. She survived her incarceration after lying about her age, resulting in her being placed in a work camp. She was freed from [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]] on April 15, 1945. After moving to the United States, she raised a family and became a public speaker, sharing her experience with students until her death, and activist.\n\n==Early life==\n\nMargit Buchhalter was born June 12, 1929, in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]].<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"OralHistory1\">{{cite web |title=Oral history interview with Margit Feldman \u2013 Collections Search \u2013 United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn504470 |website=Collections |publisher=United State Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> Her parents were Joseph and Theresa Buchhalter.<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> She had no siblings. The family lived in [[Tolcsva]], Hungary.<ref name=\"Bella\"/> \n\n===Holocaust===\nWhen she was fourteen,<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> the [[Nazi]]s invaded Tolcsva.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> Her family was moved into a [[Nazi ghetto]] in another town.<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/> In April 1944, her family was transported to [[Auschwitz]] and her parents were immediately killed in the gas chambers. Buchhalter told the German guards she was 18 years old and was sent to [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland, where she worked at a quarry.<ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/> The Germans tattooed \"A23929\" on her left arm as her identification.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> After Krak\u00f3w, she returned to Auschwitz.<ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite web |title=Margit Feldman Obituary, Somerset, New Jersey |url=http://www.brucecvanarsdalefuneralhome.com/obituary/Margit-Feldman/Somerset-New-Jersey/1871756 |website=Bruce C. Van Arsdale Funeral Home |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nBuchhalter was transported to a women's camp in [[Zielona G\u00f3ra|Gruenberg]], where she met [[Gerda Weissmann Klein]]. Buchhalter participated in the death march from Gruenberg to [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]].<ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/> On April 15, 1945, Bergen-Belsen was liberated.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> Upon liberation, Buchhalter suffered from [[pleurisy]] and [[pneumonia]]. She also suffered injuries from explosives, which were set off by German soldiers in an attempt to destroy the camp.<ref name=\"Bella\"/> Buchhalter was one of two family members to survive out of the 68 of whom were transported to concentration camps.<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> Buchhalter moved to [[Sweden]], where she recovered.<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/>\n\n==Life in the United States==\n\nBuchhalter immigrated to the United States in 1947. She moved to New York, where she lived with her aunt, Hermina Boehm, and cousins.<ref name=\"Obit\"/> She became an x-ray technician.<ref name=\"Bella\"/> In 1953, she married Harvey Feldman.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> She had met Feldman while she was recovering from [[tuberculosis]] in the hospital.<ref name=\"Obit\"/> The couple lived in [[Bound Brook, New Jersey]]. She had two children with Feldman.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> \n\n===Educator and activist===\nFeldman did not speak publicly about her experience in the Holocaust for many years. In the 1970s,<ref name=\"Bella\"/> while living in Bound Brook with her family, a boy from her neighborhood asked Feldman to speak to his elementary school class about her experience. She declined to speak to the group, but allowed the boy to record her talking about it. He proceeded to play the tape to his class. The class was deeply impacted by her story and the boy gave the feedback to Feldman, who realized the importance of sharing her experience.<ref name=\"GSBS\">{{cite web |title=Holocaust Survivor Margit Buchhalter Feldman Addresses Upper School |url=https://www.gsbschool.org/news-detail?pk=927338 |website=Gill St. Bernard's School |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en |date=24 April 2017}}</ref> \n\nFeldman co-founded the [[Raritan Valley Community College]] Institute for Holocaust & Genocide Studies in 1981.<ref name=\"Schiavi\">{{cite web |last1=Schiavi |first1=MaryLynn |title=Film chronicles the life of a woman who dared to speak the truth about Holocaust |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/local/how-we-live/2016/05/22/holocaust-survivor/84233700/ |website=My Central Jersey |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en |date=22 May 2016}}</ref> She also co-founded the New Jersey Commission on Holocaust Education with then New Jersey state assemblyman [[Jim McGreevey]] in 1991. In 1994, she supported a bill mandating Holocaust and genocide curriculum in New Jersey schools.<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\nShe served as president of the Jewish Federation of Somerset & Warren Counties and chair of the United Jewish Appeal and Israel Bonds Campaigns. She was also president of the Jewish Home for the Aged, vice president of Congregation Knesseth Israel and a member of Temple Sholom in [[Bridgewater, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\nIn 2003, she co-authored the autobiography ''Margit: A teenager's journey through the Holocaust and beyond''.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> \n\n==Later life and death==\n\nFeldman, her family, and the New Jersey Commission on Holocaust Education created the Margit Feldman Teaching Award in 2014. The award is given to New Jersey teachers who demonstrate \"outstanding\" in-class education about the Holocaust, bias, prejudice, bullying and bigotry.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Jersey Commission on Holocaust Education \u2013 Margit Feldman Teaching Award |url=https://www.nj.gov/education/holocaust/awards/feldman.html |website=State of New Jersey}}</ref> In 2016, Peppy Margolis directed a documentary about Feldman, called \"Not A23029\". [[Michael Berenbaum]] narrated the short film.<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> \n\nFeldman lived in [[Somerset, New Jersey]], until her death on April 14, 2020, from [[COVID-19]]-related complications.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/><ref name=\"Schiavi\"/>\n\n==Works by Margit Feldman==\n*with Bernard Weinstein. ''Margit: A teenager's journey through the Holocaust and beyond''. Scottsdale: Princeton Editorial Associates (2003). \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Auschwitz concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:Krak\u00f3w-P\u0142asz\u00f3w concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:Bergen-Belsen concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:People from Budapest]]\n[[Category:People from Somerset County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]]\n[[Category:People from Bound Brook, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:21st-century Jews\u200e]]\n[[Category:Jewish concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Public orators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:21st-century American educators]]\n[[Category:Jewish educators]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of the United States]]\n[[Category:American women educators]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Children in the Holocaust]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hungarian-American public speaker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Margit Buchhalter Feldman<!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image              = Margit_Feldman.png<!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Feldman in 2009\n| birth_name         = Margit Buchhalter<!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1929|06|12}}<ref name=\"Siemaszko\">{{cite news |last1=Siemaszko |first1=Corky |title=Coronavirus kills 90-year-old Holocaust survivor |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/holocaust-survivor-who-shared-her-story-students-dies-coronavirus-n1185701 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=NBC News |date=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Budapest]], Hungary<ref name=\"Bella\">{{cite news |last1=Bella |first1=Timothy |title=Holocaust survivor dies of the coronavirus 75 years after she was liberated from concentration camp |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/04/17/holocaust-survivor-coronavirus/ |accessdate=18 April 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=17 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|14|1929|06|12}}<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n| death_place        = [[Somerset, New Jersey|Somerset]], [[New Jersey]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = Complications related to [[COVID-19]]<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/>\n| nationality        = [[Hungarian-American]]\n| citizenship        = United States\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Public speaker<Br/>Educator<Br/>Activist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Holocaust survivor]]\n| notable_works      = \n| spouse             = Harvey Feldman (1953\u20132020)\n| children           = 2\n}}\n'''Margit Buchhalter Feldman''' (June 12, 1929 \u2013 April 14, 2020) was a Hungarian-American public speaker, educator, activist, and [[Holocaust survivor]]. Feldman and her family were placed in a concentration camp in 1944, where her parents were immediately killed. She survived her incarceration after lying about her age, resulting in her being placed in a work camp. She was freed from [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]] on April 15, 1945. After moving to the United States, she raised a family and became a public speaker, sharing her experience with students until her death, and activist.\n\n==Early life==\n\nMargit Buchhalter was born June 12, 1929 in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]].<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"OralHistory1\">{{cite web |title=Oral history interview with Margit Feldman \u2013 Collections Search \u2013 United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn504470 |website=Collections |publisher=United State Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> Her parents were Joseph and Theresa Buchhalter.<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> She had no siblings. The family lived in [[Tolcsva]], Hungary.<ref name=\"Bella\"/> \n\n===Holocaust===\nWhen she was fourteen,<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> the [[Nazi]]s invaded Tolcsva.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> Her family was moved into a [[Nazi ghetto]] in another town.<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/> In April 1944, her family was transported to [[Auschwitz]] and her parents were immediately killed in the gas chambers. Buchhalter told the German guards she was 18 years old and was sent to [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland, where she worked at a quarry.<ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/> The Germans tattooed \"A23929\" on her left arm as her identification.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> After Krak\u00f3w, she returned to Auschwitz.<ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite web |title=Margit Feldman Obituary, Somerset, New Jersey |url=http://www.brucecvanarsdalefuneralhome.com/obituary/Margit-Feldman/Somerset-New-Jersey/1871756 |website=Bruce C. Van Arsdale Funeral Home |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nBuchhalter was transported to a women's camp in [[Zielona G\u00f3ra|Gruenberg]], where she met [[Gerda Weissmann Klein]]. Buchhalter participated in the death march from Gruenberg to [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]].<ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/> On April 15, 1945, Bergen-Belsen was liberated.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> Upon liberation, Buchhalter suffered from [[pleurisy]] and [[pneumonia]]. She also suffered injuries from explosives, which were set off by German soldiers in an attempt to destroy the camp.<ref name=\"Bella\"/> Buchhalter was one of two family members to survive out of the 68 of whom were transported to concentration camps.<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> Buchhalter moved to [[Sweden]], where she recovered.<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"OralHistory1\"/>\n\n==Life in the United States==\n\nBuchhalter immigrated to the United States in 1947. She moved to New York, where she lived with her aunt, Hermina Boehm, and cousins.<ref name=\"Obit\"/> She became an x-ray technician.<ref name=\"Bella\"/> In 1953, she married Harvey Feldman.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> She had met Feldman while she was recovering from [[tuberculosis]] in the hospital.<ref name=\"Obit\"/> The couple lived in [[Bound Brook, New Jersey]]. She had two children with Feldman.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> \n\n===Educator and activist===\nFeldman did not speak publicly about her experience in the Holocaust for many years. In the 1970s,<ref name=\"Bella\"/> while living in Bound Brook with her family, a boy from her neighborhood asked Feldman to speak to his elementary school class about her experience. She declined to speak to the group, but allowed the boy to record her talking about it. He proceeded to play the tape to his class. The class was deeply impacted by her story and the boy gave the feedback to Feldman, who realized the importance of sharing her experience.<ref name=\"GSBS\">{{cite web |title=Holocaust Survivor Margit Buchhalter Feldman Addresses Upper School |url=https://www.gsbschool.org/news-detail?pk=927338 |website=Gill St. Bernard's School |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en |date=24 April 2017}}</ref> \n\nFeldman co-founded the [[Raritan Valley Community College]] Institute for Holocaust & Genocide Studies in 1981.<ref name=\"Schiavi\">{{cite web |last1=Schiavi |first1=MaryLynn |title=Film chronicles the life of a woman who dared to speak the truth about Holocaust |url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/local/how-we-live/2016/05/22/holocaust-survivor/84233700/ |website=My Central Jersey |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en |date=22 May 2016}}</ref> She also co-founded the New Jersey Commission on Holocaust Education with then New Jersey state assemblyman [[Jim McGreevey]] in 1991. In 1994, she supported a bill mandating Holocaust and genocide curriculum in New Jersey schools.<ref name=\"Bella\"/><ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\nShe served as president of the Jewish Federation of Somerset & Warren Counties and chair of the United Jewish Appeal and Israel Bonds Campaigns. She was also president of the Jewish Home for the Aged, vice president of Congregation Knesseth Israel and a member of Temple Sholom in [[Bridgewater, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\nIn 2003, she co-authored the autobiography ''Margit: A teenager's journey through the Holocaust and beyond''.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/> \n\n==Later life and death==\n\nFeldman, her family, and the New Jersey Commission on Holocaust Education created the Margit Feldman Teaching Award in 2014. The award is given to New Jersey teachers who demonstrate \"outstanding\" in-class education about the Holocaust, bias, prejudice, bullying and bigotry.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Jersey Commission on Holocaust Education \u2013 Margit Feldman Teaching Award |url=https://www.nj.gov/education/holocaust/awards/feldman.html |website=State of New Jersey}}</ref> In 2016, Peppy Margolis directed a documentary about Feldman, called \"Not A23029\". [[Michael Berenbaum]] narrated the short film.<ref name=\"Schiavi\"/> \n\nFeldman lived in [[Somerset, New Jersey]], until her death on April 14, 2020, from [[COVID-19]] related complications.<ref name=\"Siemaszko\"/><ref name=\"Schiavi\"/>\n\n==Works by Margit Feldman==\n*with Bernard Weinstein. ''Margit: A teenager's journey through the Holocaust and beyond''. Scottsdale: Princeton Editorial Associates (2003). \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Auschwitz concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:Krak\u00f3w-P\u0142asz\u00f3w concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:Bergen-Belsen concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:People from Budapest]]\n[[Category:People from Somerset County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]]\n[[Category:People from Bound Brook, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:21st-century Jews\u200e]]\n[[Category:Jewish concentration camp survivors\u200e]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Public orators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:21st-century American educators]]\n[[Category:Jewish educators]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of the United States]]\n[[Category:American women educators]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Hungarian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Children in the Holocaust]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margit_Feldman"}
{"title_page": "Ferr\u00e1n Corominas", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Corominas|Telechea}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Coro\n| image = Ferran_Corominas.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Coro in 2018\n| fullname = Ferr\u00e1n Corominas Telechea\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1983|1|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Vilob\u00ed d'Onyar]], Spain\n| height = 1.73 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[FC Goa|Goa]]\n| clubnumber = 8\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Vilob\u00ed\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[CD Banyoles|Banyoles]]\n| years1 = 2001\u20132004 | clubs1 = [[RCD Espanyol B|Espanyol B]] | caps1 = 103 | goals1 = 35\n| years2 = 2003\u20132011 | clubs2 = [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] | caps2 = 165 | goals2 = 14\n| years3 = 2011 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] (loan) | caps3 = 6 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs4 = [[Girona FC|Girona]] | caps4 = 40 | goals4 = 18\n| years5 = 2012\u20132015 | clubs5 = [[Elche CF|Elche]] | caps5 = 112 | goals5 = 17\n| years6 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs6 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps6 = 16 | goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 2016\u20132017 | clubs7 = [[Doxa Katokopias FC|Doxa]] | caps7 = 18 | goals7 = 5\n| years8 = 2017\u2013 | clubs8 = [[FC Goa|Goa]] | caps8 = 57 | goals8 = 48\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 2001 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain U17]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 7 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3 = 2003 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 6 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2003\u2013 | nationalteam4 = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] | nationalcaps4 = 8 | nationalgoals4 = 1\n| club-update = 7 March 2020\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Ferr\u00e1n Corominas Telechea''' (born 5 January 1983), commonly known as '''Coro''', is a Spanish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for Indian club [[FC Goa]].\n\nHe spent the majority of his professional career with [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]], appearing in 200 competitive games and scoring 24 goals. With the club, he won the [[2006 Copa del Rey Final|2006 Copa del Rey]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Vilob\u00ed d'Onyar]], [[Province of Girona|Girona]], [[Catalonia]], Coro was a product of [[RCD Espanyol]]'s youth system. He made his first-team debut on 2 November 2003 in a 0\u20132 home loss to [[Real Zaragoza]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD03/PUB/2003/11/03/EMD20031103020MDP.pdf|title=Montju\u00efc pide cabezas|trans-title=Montju\u00efc wants heads to roll|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=Andr\u00e9s|last=Astruells|language=Spanish|date=3 November 2003|accessdate=22 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085240/http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD03/PUB/2003/11/03/EMD20031103020MDP.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> but spent his first professional seasons with [[RCD Espanyol B|the reserve side]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]].\n\nIn the last matchday of [[2005\u201306 La Liga|2005\u201306]], on 13 May 2006, Coro scored a [[last-minute goal]] against [[Real Sociedad]], with that 1\u20130 win saving Espanyol's [[La Liga]] status and [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]] being relegated instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2006/05/14/pagina-22/813154/pdf.html|title=Corominas marc\u00f3 el gol de la temporada|trans-title=Corominas scored goal of the season|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Andr\u00e9s|last=Astruells|language=Spanish|date=14 May 2006|accessdate=4 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307003338/http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2006/05/14/pagina-22/813154/pdf.html|archive-date=7 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He added another in [[2006 Copa del Rey Final|the final]] of the [[Copa del Rey]], in a [[2005\u201306 Copa del Rey|4\u20131 defeat]] of Zaragoza.<ref name=COPA>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2006/04/13/pagina-14/813719/pdf.html|title=\u00a1Incre\u00edble Espanyol!|trans-title=Incredible Espanyol!|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Andr\u00e9s|last=Astruells|language=Spanish|date=13 April 2006|accessdate=6 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618203129/http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/2006/04/13/pagina-14/813719/pdf.html|archive-date=18 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCoro finished [[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]] with four league goals in 30 games, adding five in 11 contests in the team's [[2006\u201307 UEFA Cup|runner-up run]] in the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]], including one apiece in both legs of the semi-final clash against [[SV Werder Bremen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6598009.stm|title=Espanyol 3\u20130 Werder Bremen|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=26 April 2007|accessdate=20 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220213821/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6598009.stm|archive-date=20 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=535299.html|title=Coro's cool head comforts Espanyol|publisher=UEFA|first=John|last=Atkin|date=4 May 2007|accessdate=29 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023124750/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=535299.html|archive-date=23 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In the following three years combined, he amassed 75 league appearances with six goals, alternating the [[Substitute (association football)|substitutes bench]] with the starting XI.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/deportes/20071203/coro-un-revulsivo-que-pide-ser-titular-5502349|title=Coro, un revulsivo que pide ser titular|trans-title=Coro, a spark who asks to start|newspaper=[[El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalunya]]|language=Spanish|date=3 December 2007|accessdate=20 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221035605/https://www.elperiodico.com/es/deportes/20071203/coro-un-revulsivo-que-pide-ser-titular-5502349|archive-date=21 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20081107/coro-mas-que-un-comodin_53573760417.html|title=Coro, m\u00e1s que un comod\u00edn|trans-title=Coro, more than a joker|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Rogelio|last=Rom\u00e1n|language=Spanish|date=7 November 2008|accessdate=20 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220212616/http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20081107/coro-mas-que-un-comodin_53573760417.html|archive-date=20 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-January 2011, completely ostracised by manager \u2013 and former teammate at Espanyol \u2013 [[Mauricio Pochettino]], Coro signed with fellow league club [[CA Osasuna]] on loan until the end of [[2010\u201311 La Liga|the campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11827_6676245,00.html|title=Osasuna loan deal for Coro|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=19 January 2011|accessdate=29 April 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121153428/http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11827_6676245,00.html|archive-date=21 January 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> He spent the following seasons competing in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], appearing and scoring regularly for [[Girona FC]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/08/31/futbol/equipos/espanyol/1314821755.html|title=Coro firma por el Girona|trans-title=Coro signs for Girona|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=Mari Carmen|last=Torres|language=Spanish|date=31 August 2011|accessdate=6 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416032818/http://www.marca.com/2011/08/31/futbol/equipos/espanyol/1314821755.html|archive-date=16 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Elche CF]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/elche-cf/180703-coro-ficha-por-el-elche.html|title=Coro ficha por el Elche|trans-title=Coro signs for Elche|publisher=[[Vavel]]|language=Spanish|date=4 August 2012|accessdate=6 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917154918/http://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/elche-cf/180703-coro-ficha-por-el-elche.html|archive-date=17 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> he helped the latter return to the top flight in [[2012\u201313 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|his first year]], after an absence of 24 years.\n\nOn 18 July 2017, 34-year-old Coro signed for [[Indian Super League]] franchise [[FC Goa]] after a brief stint in the [[Cypriot First Division]] with [[Doxa Katokopias FC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hindustantimes.com/football/fc-goa-confirm-signing-of-spanish-midfielder-ferran-corominas/story-GGpTNnTaiYCfF1Myrk120J_amp.html|title=FC Goa confirm signing of Spanish midfielder Ferran Corominas|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=18 July 2017|accessdate=19 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719053628/http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/fc-goa-confirm-signing-of-spanish-midfielder-ferran-corominas/story-GGpTNnTaiYCfF1Myrk120J_amp.html|archive-date=19 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 19 November, finding the net in the 25th minute of a 3\u20132 away victory over [[Chennaiyin FC]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/sports/football/191117/isl-2017-18-ferran-corominas-shines-as-fc-goa-beat-chennaiyin-fc-in-5-goal-thriller.html|title=ISL 2017\u201318: Ferran Corominas shines as FC Goa beat Chennaiyin FC in 5-goal thriller|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|date=19 November 2017|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222164053/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/sports/football/191117/isl-2017-18-ferran-corominas-shines-as-fc-goa-beat-chennaiyin-fc-in-5-goal-thriller.html|archive-date=22 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> two [[hat-tricks]] followed on 30 November and 9 December, helping the hosts defeat [[Bengaluru FC]] (4\u20133)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/isl-fc-goa-beat-10-man-bengaluru-4-3-in-thriller/articleshow/61869560.cms|title=ISL: FC Goa beat 10-man Bengaluru 4\u20133 in thriller|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=30 November 2017|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223183241/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/isl-fc-goa-beat-10-man-bengaluru-4-3-in-thriller/articleshow/61869560.cms|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Kerala Blasters FC]] (5\u20132),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ferran-corominas-fc-goa-vs-kerala-blasters-isl-2017/1/1106925.html|title=ISL: Ferran Corominas scored second consecutive hat-trick to help FC Goa thrash Kerala Blasters|newspaper=[[India Today]]|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216222304/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ferran-corominas-fc-goa-vs-kerala-blasters-isl-2017/1/1106925.html|archive-date=16 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and he eventually won the [[Indian Super League Golden Boot|Golden Boot]] with 18 goals.<ref name=GOLDEN>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/football/sunil-chhetri-named-hero-of-indian-super-league-ferran-corominas-wins-golden-boot/story-0DrkyJekuBHtDAG1jLJCvO.html|title=Sunil Chhetri named \u2018Hero\u2019 of Indian Super League, Ferran Corominas wins Golden Boot|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=18 March 2018|access-date=18 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319032412/https://www.hindustantimes.com/football/sunil-chhetri-named-hero-of-indian-super-league-ferran-corominas-wins-golden-boot/story-0DrkyJekuBHtDAG1jLJCvO.html|archive-date=19 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2018, Coro renewed his contract by one year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcgoa.in/news-details.php?id=197|title=Ferran Corominas extends stay with FC Goa|publisher=FC Goa|date=30 April 2018|access-date=12 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501004339/http://www.fcgoa.in/news-details.php?id=197|archive-date=1 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He continued his good form [[2018\u201319 Indian Super League season|the following season]] by scoring a league-best 16 goals, also being awarded the Golden Ball and helping his team reach [[2019 Indian Super League Final|the finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/lists/isl-2018-19-list-of-award-winners-coro-gurpreet/uyvd3xu0f1g91foek8go8nmb2|title=ISL 2018\u201319: List of award winners|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=17 March 2019|accessdate=25 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525181346/https://www.goal.com/en-in/lists/isl-2018-19-list-of-award-winners-coro-gurpreet/uyvd3xu0f1g91foek8go8nmb2|archive-date=25 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May 2019, Coro agreed to another extension at the [[Fatorda Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/sports/indian-super-league-fc-goa-forward-ferran-corominas-extends-stay-at-club-for-another-year-6701051.html|title=Indian Super League: FC Goa forward Ferran Corominas extends stay at club for another year|publisher=[[Firstpost]]|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=25 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525181347/https://www.firstpost.com/sports/indian-super-league-fc-goa-forward-ferran-corominas-extends-stay-at-club-for-another-year-6701051.html|archive-date=25 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{Updated|match played on 19 February 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=